      "bodyTr": "PoINT Technology, a deeptech startup co-founded by Bae Hyun-min, director of KAIST's Entrepreneurship Center, has attracted 76 million dollars (approximately 112.7 billion won) in investment from overseas investors including Nvidia. This marks the first time a domestic semiconductor startup has secured strategic investment from Nvidia. It is an encouraging case demonstrating that cutting-edge technology from university laboratories can be recognized as disruptive innovation technology in the global market.\n\nThe key to this investment is the 'e-tube' technology. It can extend transmission distance tenfold compared to copper wires while reducing power consumption and costs to one-third compared to optical cables. The fact that the demanding Nvidia opened its wallet directly for this technology means the world has recognized its potential to become a core competitive advantage for future AI data centers.\n\nWhile welcoming this news, there is a lingering regret: why has this core technology created by Korea's finest minds blossomed in the arms of overseas companies rather than our domestic conglomerates? Attracting foreign capital is certainly cause for celebration, but ultimately seeing domestic innovation assets and leadership transfer to becoming an American company's growth engine is a painful matter from the perspective of our ecosystem. Had domestic conglomerates invested proactively, it would have transcended mere capital injection to become a model case of 'open innovation' for the domestic industry, and offered an opportunity for the conglomerates themselves to equip powerful new growth engines.\n\nWe must reflect on whether the structural limitations that force promising technologies to turn away from the domestic market and look overseas have once again been exposed. Fortunately, signs of change are emerging. Cases are beginning to appear where conglomerates like Samsung and Hanwha recognize startups as partners and embrace them as future growth drivers through investments in Rainbow Robotics and the acquisition of Satrec Initiative. A paradigm shift is occurring in industry circles, viewing technology not as something to be taken away but as something to be nurtured together. This open innovation culture must be further activated.\n\nOnly when large corporations become a backbone for startups and startups become new growth engines for large corporations can Korea break through its growth limitations and truly become a genuine 'first mover.' Nvidia's investment is a warning shot to our conglomerates and a powerful mandate to transform the paradigm of the innovation ecosystem.",
